JOHANNESBURG, Dec. 19 (Xinhua) -- As the Omicron variant continues spreading across South Africa, Mineral Resources and Energy Minister Gwede Mantashe has tested positive for COVID-19. A statement released on Sunday revealed that Mantashe tested positive on Saturday after experiencing mild symptoms. "Minister Mantashe is in good spirits and he is currently in self-isolation," a statement said. This is the second time the minister tests positive for COVID-19. Mantashe's positive tests came after President Cyril Ramaphosa who also tested positive after returning from a West African trip. Ramaphosa has been in isolation since then. "Government urges all South Africans to vaccinate and remain disciplined in observing all COVID-19 safety protocols to ensure a safe and joyful festive season with family and friends," notes a statement by The Presidency released on Sunday. The National Institute for Communicable Diseases (NICD) said on Saturday that 16,080 new COVID-19 cases have been identified in South Africa, which brought the total number of laboratory-confirmed cases to 3,292,609. There were 48 COVID-19 related deaths reported, bringing total fatalities to 90,345 to date. Enditem